url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/August
title: August
text: August (Aug.) is the eighth month of the year in the Gregorian calendar, coming between July and September. It has 31 days. It is named after the Roman emperor Augustus Caesar.

id: August does not begin on the same day of the week as any other month in common years
url: but begins on the same day of the week as February in leap years. August always ends on the same day of the week as November.

id: This month was first called Sextilis in Latin
url: because it was the sixth month in the old Roman calendar. The Roman calendar began in March about 735 BC with Romulus. October was the eighth month. August was the eighth month when January or February were added to the start of the year by King Numa Pompilius about 700 BC. Or
title: when those two months were moved from the end to the beginning of the year by the decemvirs about 450 BC (Roman writers disagree). In 153 BC January 1 was determined as the beginning of the year.

id: August is named for Augustus Caesar who became Roman consul in this month. The month has 31 days because Julius Caesar added two days when he created the Julian calendar in 45 BC. August is after July and before September.

url: in either hemisphere
title: is the seasonal equivalent of February in the other. In the Northern hemisphere it is a summer month and it is a winter month in the Southern hemisphere.

id: No other month in common years begins on the same day of the week as August

id: The letter 'A' was in the Phoenician alphabet's aleph. This symbol came from a simple picture of an ox head.

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air
title: Air
text: Air refers to the Earth's atmosphere. Air is a mixture of many gases and tiny dust particles. It is the clear gas in which living things live and breathe. It has an indefinite shape and volume. It has mass and weight, because it is matter. The weight of air creates atmospheric  pressure. There is no air in outer space.

id: Air is a mixture of about 78% of nitrogen
url: 21% of oxygen
title: 0.9% of argon
text: 0.04% of carbon dioxide
title_vector: and very small amounts of other gases.  There is an average of about 1% water vapour.

id: Animals live and need to breathe the oxygen in the air. In breathing
url: the lungs put oxygen into the blood
title: and send back carbon dioxide to the air. Plants need the carbon dioxide in the air to live. They give off the oxygen that we breathe. Without it we die of asphyxia.

url: this is refreshing. This causes weather.

id: Air can be polluted by some gases (such as carbon monoxide
url: hydrocarbons
title: and nitrogen oxides)
text: smoke
title_vector: and ash. This air pollution causes various problems including smog
content_vector: acid rain and global warming. It can damage people's health and the environment.

url: air has been used to create technology. Ships moved with sails and windmills used the mechanical motion of air. Aircraft use propellers to move air over a wing
title: which allows them to fly. Pneumatics use air pressure to move things. Since the late 1900s
text: air power is also used to generate electricity.

id: Air is invisible: it cannot be seen by the eye
url: though a shimmering in hot air can be seen.

id: Air is one of the four classical elements in Greek theory. It was considered an intervening element
url: somewhere between fire and water
title: and the driving force for the birth of the cosmos.

id: Earth's atmosphere has changed much since its formation.
At first it was mainly a hydrogen atmosphere. It  has changed dramatically on several occasions—for example
url: the Great Oxygenation Event 2.4 billion years ago
title: greatly increased oxygen in the atmosphere from practically no oxygen to levels closer to present day. Humans have also contributed to significant changes in atmospheric composition through air pollution
text: especially since industrialisation
title_vector: leading to rapid environmental change such as ozone depletion and global warming.

url: supplemented by gases produced during the late heavy bombardment of Earth by huge asteroids
title: produced the next atmosphere
text: consisting largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide and inert gases.

id: The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere. Carbon dioxide was transferred to and from large continental carbonate stores. Free oxygen did not exist in the atmosphere until about 2.4 billion years ago. The Great Oxygenation Event is shown by the end of the banded iron formations.

id: Educated in Dublin at Alexandra School and College; on October 1st 1907 she married Julius Mathison Turing
url: latter son of Reverend John Robert Turing and Fanny Boyd
title: in Dublin. Born on June 23rd 1912
text: Alan Turing would go on to be regarded as one of the greatest figures of the twentieth century.

id: A brilliant mathematician and cryptographer Alan was to become the founder of modern-day computer science and artificial intelligence; designing a machine at Bletchley Park to break secret Enigma encrypted messages used by the Nazi German war machine to protect sensitive commercial
url: diplomatic and military communications during World War 2. Thus
title: Turing made the single biggest contribution to the Allied victory in the war against Nazi Germany
text: possibly saving the lives of an estimated 2 million people
title_vector: through his effort in shortening World War II.

url: almost 60 years later
title: Turing received a posthumous Royal Pardon from Queen Elizabeth II. Today
text: the “Turing law” grants an automatic pardon to men who died before the law came into force
title_vector: making it possible for living convicted gay men to seek pardons for offences now no longer on the statute book.

url: Turing accidentally or otherwise lost his life in 1954
title: having been subjected by a British court to chemical castration
text: thus avoiding a custodial sentence. He is known to have ended his life at the age of 41 years
title_vector: by eating an apple laced with cyanide.

id: Turing was one of the people who worked on the first computers. He created the theoretical  Turing machine in 1936. The machine was imaginary
url: but it included the idea of a computer program.

id: Turing was interested in artificial intelligence. He proposed the Turing test
url: to say when a machine could be called ""intelligent"". A computer could be said to ""think"" if a human talking with it could not tell it was a machine.
Turing worked with others to break German ciphers (secret messages). He  worked for the Government Code and Cypher School (GC&CS) at Bletchley Park
title: Britain's codebreaking centre that produced Ultra intelligence.

url: he helped to break the codes of the Enigma machine. After that
title: he worked on other German codes.

url: Turing worked on the design of the ACE (Automatic Computing Engine) at the National Physical Laboratory. He presented a paper on 19 February 1946. That paper was ""the first detailed design of a stored-program computer"". Although it was possible to build ACE
title: there were delays in starting the project. In late 1947 he returned to Cambridge for a sabbatical year. While he was at Cambridge
text: the Pilot ACE was built without him. It ran its first program on 10 May 1950.

id: Turing was a homosexual man. In 1952
url: he admitted having had sex with a man in England. At that time
title: homosexual acts were illegal. Turing was convicted. He had to choose between going to jail and taking hormones to lower his sex drive. He decided to take the hormones. After his punishment
text: he became impotent. He also grew breasts.

url: a private member's bill was put before the House of Lords to grant Turing a statutory pardon. In July 2013
title: the government supported it. A royal pardon was granted on 24 December 2013.

url: Turing died from cyanide poisoning. The cyanide came from either an apple which was poisoned with cyanide
title: or from water that had cyanide in it. The reason for the confusion is that the police never tested the apple for cyanide. It is also suspected that he committed suicide.

id: The treatment forced on him is now believed to be very wrong. It is against medical ethics and international laws of human rights. In August 2009
url: a petition asking the British Government to apologise to Turing for punishing him for being a homosexual was started. The petition received thousands of signatures. Prime Minister Gordon Brown acknowledged the petition. He called Turing's treatment ""appalling"".

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farming
title: Farming
text: Farming is growing crops and keeping animals  for food and raw materials. Farming is a part of agriculture.

id: Agriculture started thousands of years ago
url: but no one knows for sure how old it is. The development of farming gave rise to the Neolithic Revolution as people gave up nomadic hunting and became settlers in cities.

id: Agriculture and domestication probably started in the Fertile Crescent (the Nile Valley
url: the Levant and Mesopotamia). The area called Fertile Crescent is now in the countries of Iraq
title: Syria
text: Turkey
title_vector: Jordan
content_vector: Lebanon
vector_id: Israel

id: This allowed the human population to grow to such large numbers as there are today.

Arable farming means growing crops. This would include wheat or vegetables. Growing fruit means having orchards devoted to fruit. They cannot be switched easily with growing  field crops. Therefore they are not classed as arable land in the statistics.
Agriculture is not only growing food for people and animals
url: but also growing other things like flowers and nursery plants
title: manure or dung
text: animal hides (skins or furs)
title_vector: leather
content_vector: animals
vector_id: fungi

id: Many people still live by subsistence agriculture
url: on a small farm. They can only grow enough food to feed the farmer
title: his family
text: and his animals. The yield is the amount of food grown on a given amount of land
title_vector: and it is often low. This is because subsistence farmers are generally less educated
content_vector: and they have less money to buy equipment. Drought and other problems sometimes cause famines. Where yields are low
vector_id: deforestation can provide new land to grow more food. This provides more nutrition for the farmer's family

url: farms are often fewer and larger. During the 20th century they have become more productive because farmers are able to grow better varieties of plants
title: use more fertilizer
text: use more water
title_vector: and more easily control weeds and pests. Many farms also use machines
content_vector: so fewer people can farm more land. There are fewer farmers in rich countries
vector_id: but the farmers are able to grow more.

id: This kind of intensive agriculture comes with its own set of problems. Farmers use a lot of chemical fertilizers
url: pesticides (chemicals that kill bugs)
title: and herbicides (chemicals that kill weeds). These chemicals can pollute the soil or the water. They can also create bugs and weeds that are more resistant to the chemicals
text: causing outbreaks of these pests. The soil can be damaged by erosion (blowing or washing away)
title_vector: salt buildup
content_vector: or loss of structure. Irrigation (adding water from rivers) can pollute water and lower the water table. These problems have all got solutions
vector_id: and modern young farmers usually have a good technical education.

id: Farmers select plants with better yield
url: taste
title: and nutritional value. They also choose plants that can survive plant disease and drought
text: and are easier to harvest. Centuries of artificial selection and breeding have changed crop plants. The crops produce better yield. Fertilizers
title_vector: chemical pest control
content_vector: and irrigation all help.

id: Some plants are improved with  genetic engineering. One example is modifying the plant to resist herbicides.
It is important for there to be enough food for everyone. The food must also be safe and good. People say it is not always safe
url: because it contains some chemicals. Other people say intensive agriculture is damaging the environment. For this reason
title: there are several types of agriculture.

id: Traditional agriculture is mostly done in poor countries.
Intensive agriculture is mostly done in countries with more money. It uses pesticides
url: machinery
title: chemical fertilizers.

id: Organic farming is using only natural products such as compost and green manure.
Integrated farming is using local resources
url: and trying to use the waste from one process as a resource in another process.

id: Agricultural policy focuses on the goals and methods of agricultural production. Common goals of policy include the quality
url: amount
title: and safety of food.

id: There are some serious problems that people face trying to grow food today.
The major crops produced in the world in 2002
url: are maize (corn)
title: wheat
text: rice
title_vector: and cotton.

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia
title: Australia
text: Australia, formally the Commonwealth of Australia, is a country and sovereign state in the southern hemisphere, located in Oceania. Its capital city is Canberra, and its largest city is Sydney.

id: Australia is the sixth biggest country in the world by land area
url: and is part of the Oceanic and Australasian regions. Australia
title: New Zealand
text: New Guinea and other islands on the Australian tectonic plate are together called Australasia
title_vector: which is one of the world's great ecozones. When other Pacific islands are included with Australasia
content_vector: it is called Oceania.

url: and about 85% of them live near the east coast.  The country is divided up into six states and two territories
title: and more than half of Australia's population lives in and around the cities of Sydney
text: Melbourne
title_vector: Brisbane
content_vector: Perth
vector_id: Canberra and Adelaide. The first people to live in the country were Indigenous Australians but most of them died from smallpox during colonization.

id: Australia is known for its mining (coal
url: iron
title: gold
text: diamonds and crystals)
title_vector: its production of wool
content_vector: and as the world's largest producer of bauxite. Its emblem is a flower called the Golden Wattle.

id: Australia is also known for its animals and rich wildlife. A Kangaroo is the national symbol of Australia.

title: 930 square kilometers is on the Indo-Australian plate. The continent of Australia
text: including the island of Tasmania
title_vector: was separated from the other continents of the world many millions of years ago. Because of this
content_vector: many animals and plants live in Australia that do not live anywhere else. These include animals like the kangaroo
vector_id: the koala

id: People first arrived in Australia more than 50
url: 000 years ago. These native Australians are called the Australian Aborigines. For the history of Australia
title: see History of Australia.

url: having been settled from Britain
title: became mostly independent democratic states in the 1850s and all six combined as a federation on 1 January 1901. The first Prime Minister of Australia was Edmund Barton in 1901. Australia is a member of the United Nations and the Commonwealth of Nations. It is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy with Elizabeth II as Queen of Australia and Head of State and a Governor-General who is chosen by the Prime Minister to carry out all the duties of the Queen in Australia.

url: two major mainland territories
title: and other minor territories. The states are New South Wales
text: Queensland
title_vector: South Australia
content_vector: Tasmania
vector_id: Victoria

id: In 2013 according to world bank Australia had just over 23.13 million people. Most Australians live in cities along the coast
url: such as Sydney
title: Melbourne
text: Brisbane
title_vector: Perth
content_vector: Darwin
vector_id: Hobart and Adelaide. The largest inland city is Canberra

id: Australia is a very big country
url: but much of the land is very dry
title: and the middle of the continent is mostly desert. Only the areas around the east
text: west and south coast have enough rain and a suitable climate (not too hot) for many farms and cities.

id: The Australian Aboriginal people arrived in Australia about 50
url: 000 years ago or even earlier. Until the arrival of British settlers in 1788
title: the Aboriginal people lived by hunting and gathering food from the land. They lived in all sorts of climates and managed the land in different ways. An example of Aboriginal land management was the Cumberland Plain where Sydney is now. Every few years the Aboriginal people would burn the grass and small trees. This meant that a lot of grass grew back
text: but not many big trees. Kangaroos like to live on grassy plains
title_vector: but not in forests. The kangaroos that lived on the plain were a good food supply for the Aboriginal people. Sometimes
content_vector: Aborigines would name a person after an animal
vector_id: and they could not eat that animal to help level out the food population.

id: Aboriginal people did not usually build houses
url: except huts of grass
title: leaves and bark. They did not usually build walls or fences
text: and there were no horses
title_vector: cows or sheep in Australia that needed to be kept in pens. The only Aboriginal buildings that are known are fish-traps made from stones piled up in the river
content_vector: and the remains of a few stone huts in Victoria and Tasmania. The Aboriginal people did not use metal or make pottery or use bows and arrows or weave cloth. In some parts of Australia the people used sharp flaked-stone spearheads
vector_id: but most Aboriginal spears were made of sharply pointed wood. Australia has a lot of trees that have very hard wood that was good for spear making. The boomerang was used in some areas for sport and for hunting.

id: The Aboriginal people did not think that the land belonged to them. They believed that they had grown from the land
url: so it was like their mother
title: and they belonged to the land.

url: Dutch merchants traded with the islands of Batavia (now Indonesia)
title: to the north of Australia and several different Dutch ships touched on the coast of Australia. The Dutch governor
text: van Diemen
title_vector: sent Abel Tasman on a voyage of discovery and he found Tasmania
content_vector: which he named Van Diemen's Land. Its name was later changed to honour the man who discovered it.

id: The British Government was sure that there must be a very large land in the south
url: that had not been explored. They sent Captain James Cook to the Pacific Ocean. His ship
title: HMS Endeavour
text: carried the famous scientists
title_vector: Sir Joseph Banks and Dr Solander who were going to Tahiti where they would watch the planet Venus pass in front of the Sun. Captain Cook's secret mission was to find ""Terra Australis"" (the Land of the South).

id: The voyage of discovery was very successful
url: because they found New Zealand and sailed right around it. Then they sailed westward. At last
title: a boy
text: William Hicks
title_vector: who was up the mast spotted land on the horizon. Captain Cook named that bit of land Point Hicks. They sailed up the coast and Captain Cook named the land that he saw ""New South Wales"". At last they sailed into a large open bay which was full of fish and stingrays which the sailors speared for food. Joseph Banks and Dr. Solander went ashore and were astonished to find that they did not know what any of the plants or birds or animals that they saw were. They collected hundreds of plants to take back to England.

id: Captain Cook saw the Aboriginal people with their simple way of life. He saw them fishing and hunting and collecting grass seeds and fruit. But there were no houses and no fences. In most parts of the world
url: people put up a house and a fence or some marker to show that they own the land. But the Aboriginal people did not own the land in that way. They belonged to the land
title: like a baby belongs to its mother. Captain Cook went home to England and told the government that no-one owned the land. This would later cause a terrible problem for the Aboriginal people.

url: in England
title: laws were tough
text: many people were poor and gaols (jails) were full. A person could be sentenced to death for stealing a loaf of bread. Many people were hanged for small crimes. But usually they were just thrown in gaol. Often they were sent away to the British colonies in America. But by the 1770s
title_vector: the colonies in America became the United States. They were free from British rule and would not take England's convicts any more
content_vector: so England needed to find a new and less populated place.

id: By the 1780s the gaols of England were so full that convicts were often chained up in rotting old ships. The government decided to make a settlement in New South Wales and send some of the convicts there. In 1788 the First Fleet of eleven ships set sail from Portsmouth carrying convicts
url: sailors
title: marines
text: a few free settlers and enough food to last for two years. Their leader was Captain Arthur Phillip. They were to make a new colony at the place that Captain Cook had discovered
title_vector: named Botany Bay because of all the unknown plants found there by the two scientists.

id: Captain Phillip found that Botany Bay was flat and windy. There was not much fresh water. He went with two ships up the coast and sailed into a great harbor which he said was ""the finest harbor in the world!"" There were many small bays on the harbor so he decided on one which had a good stream of fresh water and some flat shore to land on. On 26 January 1788
url: the flag was raised and New South Wales was claimed in the name of King George III of England
title: and the new settlement was called Sydney.

id: For the first few years of the settlement
url: things were very difficult. No-one in the British Government had thought very hard about what sort of convicts should be sent to make a new colony. Nobody had chosen them carefully. There was only one man who was a farmer. There was no-one among the convicts who was a builder
title: a brick-maker or a blacksmith. No-one knew how to fix the tools when they broke. All of the cattle escaped. There were no cooking pots. All the plants were different so no-one knew which ones could be eaten. It was probable that everyone in the new colony would die of starvation.

url: the little group of tents with a hut for the Governor
title: Arthur Phillip
text: and another hut for the supply of food
title_vector: grew into a small town with streets
content_vector: a bridge over the stream
vector_id: a windmill for grinding grain and wharves for ships. By the 1820s there was a fine brick house for the Governor. There was also a hospital and a convict barracks and a beautiful church which are still standing today. Settlements had spread out from Sydney

id: While the settlement was growing in New South Wales
url: it was also growing in Tasmania. The climate in Tasmania was more like that in England
title: and farmers found it easy to grow crops there.

id: Because Australia is such a very large land
url: it was easy to think that it might be able to hold a very large number of people. In the early days of the colony
title: a great number of explorers went out
text: searching for good land to settle on.

id: When the settlers looked west from Sydney
url: they saw a range of mountains which they called the Blue Mountains. They were not very high and did not look very rugged but for many years no-one could find their way through them. In 1813 Gregory Blaxland
title: William Lawson and a 17-year-old called William Charles Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains and found land on the other side which was good for farming. A road was built and the governor
text: Lachlan Macquarie founded the town of Bathurst on the other side
title_vector: 100 miles from Sydney.

url: like Captain Charles Sturt were sure that there must be a sea in the middle of Australia and set out to find it. Many of the explorers did not prepare very well
title: or else they went out to explore at the hottest time of year. Some died like Burke and Wills. Ludwig Leichhardt got lost twice. The second time
text: he was never seen again. Major Thomas Mitchell was one of the most successful explorers. He mapped the country as he went
title_vector: and his maps remained in use for more than 100 years. He travelled all the way to what is now western Victoria
content_vector: and to his surprise and annoyance found that he was not the first white person there. The Henty brothers had come from Tasmania
vector_id: had built themselves a house

id: The gold rushes of New South Wales and Victoria started in 1851 leading to large numbers of people arriving to search for gold. The population grew across south east Australia and made great wealth and industry. By 1853 the gold rushes had made some poor people
url: very rich.

id: The transportation of convicts to Australia ended in the 1840s and 1850s and more changes came. The people in Australia wanted to run their own country
url: and not be told what to do from London. The first governments in the colonies were run by governors chosen by London. Soon the settlers wanted local government and more democracy. William Wentworth started the Australian Patriotic Association (Australia's first political party) in 1835 to demand democratic government. In 1840
title: the city councils started and some people could vote. New South Wales Legislative Council had its first elections in 1843
text: again with some limits on who could vote. In 1855
title_vector: limited self-government was given by London to New South Wales
content_vector: Victoria
vector_id: South Australia and Tasmania. In 1855

id: Australians had started parliamentary democracies all across the continent. But voices were getting louder for all of them to come together as one country with a national parliament.

url: Australia was not a nation
title: it was six separate colonies governed by Britain. They voted to join together to form one new country
text: called the Commonwealth of Australia
title_vector: in 1901. Australia was still part of the British Empire
content_vector: and at first wanted only British or Europeans to come to Australia. But soon it had its own money
vector_id: and its own Army and Navy.

url: the trade unions were very strong
title: and they started a political party
text: the Australian Labor Party. Australia passed many laws to help the workers.

url: the First World War started in Europe. Australia joined in on the side of Britain against Germany
title: Austria-Hungary and the Ottoman Empire. Australian soldiers were sent to Gallipoli
text: in the Ottoman Empire. They fought bravely
title_vector: but were beaten by the Turks. Today Australia remembers this battle every year on ANZAC Day. They also fought on the Western Front. More than 60
content_vector: 000 Australians were killed.

id: Australia had a really hard time in the Great Depression of the 1930s and joined Britain in a war against Nazi Germany when Hitler invaded Poland in 1939. But in 1941 lots of Australian soldiers were captured in the Fall of Singapore by Japan. Then Japan started attacking Australia and people worried about invasion. But with help from the United States Navy
url: the Japanese were stopped. After the war
title: Australia became a close friend of the United States.

url: Australia felt that it needed many more people to fill the country up and to work. So the government said it would take in people from Europe who had lost their homes in the war. It did things like building the Snowy Mountains Scheme. Over the next 25 years
title: millions of people came to Australia. They came especially from Italy and Greece
text: other countries in Europe. Later they also came from countries like Turkey and Lebanon. An important new party

text: they are attacking the person they are arguing against

id: Ad hominem can be a way to use reputation
url: rumors and hearsay to change the minds of other people listening. When a social network has already excluded or exiled one person
title: or applied a negative label to them
text: this can work more often.

id: It is most of the time considered to be a weak and poor argument. In courts and in diplomacy ad hominems are not appreciated.

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Native%20American
title: Native American
text: Native Americans (also called Aboriginal Americans, American Indians, Amerindians or indigenous peoples of the Americas) are the people and their descendants, who were in the Americas when Europeans arrived.

id: Sometimes these people are called Indians
url: but this may be confusing
title: because it is the same word used for people from India. When Christopher Columbus explored
text: he did not know about the Americas. He was in the Caribbean but thought he was in the East Indies
title_vector: so he called the people Indians.

id: There are many different tribes of Native American people
url: with many different languages. Some tribes were hunter-gatherers who moved from place to place. Others lived in one place and built cities and kingdoms.

id: Many Native Americans died after the Europeans came to the Americas. There were diseases that came with the Europeans but were new to the Native Americans. There were battles with the Europeans. Many native people were hurt
url: killed
title: or forced to leave their homes by settlers who took their lands.

url: there are more than three million Native Americans in Canada and the U.S. combined. About 51 million more Native Americans live in Latin America. Many Native Americans still speak native languages and have their own cultural practices
title: while others have adopted some parts of Western culture. Many Native Americans face problems with discrimination and racism.

id: The ancestors of Native Americans came to the Americas from Asia. Some of them may have come to America 15
url: 000 years ago when Alaska was connected to Siberia by the Bering land bridge.

id: The earliest people in the Americas came from Siberia when there was an ice bridge across the Bering Strait. The cold but mainly grassy plain which connected Siberia with Canada is called Beringia.  It is reckoned that a few thousand people arrived in  Beringia from eastern Siberia during the Last Glacial Maximum before moving into the Americas sometime after 16
url: 500 years before the present (BP). This would have occurred as the American glaciers blocking the way southward melted
title: but before the bridge was covered by the sea about 11
text: 000 years BP.

url: Beringia was inhabited by the Yupik peoples on both sides of the straits. This culture remains in the region today
title: with others. In 2012
text: the governments of Russia and the United States announced a plan to formally establish ""a transboundary area of shared Beringian heritage"". Among other things this agreement would establish close ties between the Bering Land Bridge National Preserve and the Cape Krusenstern National Monument in the United States and Beringia National Park in Russia.

id: Native Americans are divided into many small nations
url: called First Nations in Canada and tribes elsewhere.

id: Each Native American tribe has their own culture. The cultures can be grouped together depending on region. For example
url: the tribes living in Mesoamerica have similar cultures.

id: Native Americans ate many different things depending on where they lived.
Native Americans from Mesoamerica introduced vanilla
url: avocados
title: and chocolate to the world.

url: the native peoples of the Americans practiced many different religions. Each tribe had their own different beliefs.
many Native Americans practice Christianity
title: a religion that was brought to the Americas by Europeans. Meanwhile
text: others still practice their own religions.

id: Native Americans today speak over a thousand different languages. Some of these languages had writing systems before Europeans came.
Many of these languages are endangered because more people are speaking European languages and not teaching Native American languages to their kids.
Native Americans make musical instruments using the things around them.
Native Americans make a lot of different art.

url: 0.9% of Americans say they are Native American

text: and 1.7% of Americans say they are both Native American and something else.  They are not evenly spread out through the United States.  About a third of the people in Alaska are Native Alaskan and about a sixth of the people in Oklahoma are Native American.

url: most Native Americans live in cities.  About 28% of Native Americans live on reservations.  Many Native Americans are poor
title: and 24% are extremely poor.  The history of violence against Native Americans persists today in higher rates of violence against Native American people than white people.

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple
title: Apple
text: Apple is the edible fruit of a number of trees, known for this juicy, green or red fruits. The tree (Malus spp.) is grown worldwide. Its fruit is low-cost and popular, and is harvested all over the world.

id: Applewood is a type of wood that comes from this tree.
The apple tree comes from southern Kazakhstan
url: Kyrgyzstan
title: Uzbekistan
text: and northwestern part of China. Apples have been grown for thousands of years in Asia and Europe. They were brought to North America by European settlers. Apples have religious and mythological significance in many cultures.

id: Apples are generally propagated by grafting
url: although wild apples grow readily from seed. Apple trees are large if grown from seed
title: but small if grafted onto roots (rootstock). There are more than 10000 known cultivars of apples
text: with a range of desired characteristics. Different cultivars are bred for various tastes and uses: cooking
title_vector: eating raw and cider production are the most common uses.

id: Trees and fruit are attacked by fungi
url: bacteria and pests. In 2010
title: the fruit's genome was sequenced as part of research on disease control and selective breeding in apple production.

id: Worldwide production of apples in 2013 was 90.8 million tonnes. China grew 49% of the total.

url: leaf-shedding tree that grows up to  tall. The apple tree has a broad crown with thick twigs.

id: The leaves are alternately arranged simple ovals. They are 5 to 12 centimetres long and 3–6 centimetres (1.2–2.4 in) wide. It has a sharp top with a soft underside. Blossoms come out in spring at the same time that the leaves begin to bud. The flowers are white. They also have a slightly pink color. They are five petaled
url: and 2.5 to 3.5 centimetres (0.98 to 1.4 in) in diameter. The fruit matures in autumn. It is usually 5 to 9 centimetres (2.0 to 3.5 in) in diameter. There are five carpels arranged in a star in the middle of the fruit. Every carpel has one to three seeds.

id: The wild ancestor of apple trees is Malus sieversii. They grow wild in the mountains of Central Asia in the north of Kazakhstan
url: Kyrgyzstan
title: Tajikistan
text: and Xinjiang
title_vector: China
content_vector: and possibly also Malus sylvestris. Unlike domesticated apples
vector_id: their leaves become red in autumn. They are being used recently to develop Malus domestica to grow in colder climates.

id: The apple tree was possibly the earliest tree to be cultivated. Its fruits have become better over thousands of years. It is said that Alexander the Great discovered dwarf apples in Asia Minor in 300 BC. Asia and Europe have used winter apples as an important food for thousands of years. From when Europeans arrived
url: Argentina and the United States have used apples as food as well. Apples were brought to North America in the 1600s. The first apple orchard on the North American continent was said to be near Boston in 1625. In the 1900s
title: costly fruit industries
text: where the apple was a very important species
title_vector: began developing.

url: the goddess Iðunn gives apples to the gods in Prose Edda (written in the 13th century by Snorri Sturluson) that makes them young forever. English scholar H. R. Ellis Davidson suggests that apples were related to religious practices in Germanic paganism. It was from there
title: she claims
text: that Norse paganism developed. She points out that buckets of apples were discovered in the place of burial for the Oseberg ship in Norway. She also remarks that fruit and nuts (Iðunn having been described as changing into a nut in Skáldskaparmál) have been discovered in the early graves of the Germanic peoples in England. They have also been discovered somewhere else on the continent of Europe. She suggests that this may have had a symbolic meaning. Nuts are still a symbol of fertility in Southwest England.

id: Sometimes apples are eaten after they are cooked. Often apples are eaten uncooked. Apples can also be made into drinks. Apple juice and apple cider are apple drinks.
The flesh of the fruit is firm with a taste anywhere from sour to sweet. Apples used for cooking are sour
url: and need to be cooked with sugar
title: while other apples are sweet
text: and do not need cooking. There are some seeds at the core
title_vector: that can be removed with a tool that removes the core
content_vector: or by carefully using a knife.

id: The scientific name of the apple tree genus in the Latin language is Malus. Most apples that people grow are of the Malus domestica species.
Most apples are good to eat raw (not cooked)
url: and are also used in many kinds of baked foods
title: such as apple pie. Apples are cooked until they are soft to make apple sauce.

id: Apples are also made into the drinks apple juice and cider. Usually
url: cider contains a little alcohol
title: about as much as beer. The regions of Brittany in France and Cornwall in England are known for their apple ciders.

id: If one wants to grow a certain type of apple it is not possible to do this by planting a seed from the wanted type. The seed will have DNA from the apple that the seeds came from
url: but it will also  have DNA from the apple flower that pollinated the seeds
title: which may well be a different type. This means that the tree which would grow from planting would be a mixture of two. In order to grow a certain type of apple
text: a small twig
title_vector: or 'scion'
content_vector: is cut from the tree that grows the type of apple desired
vector_id: and then added on to a specially grown stump called a rootstock. The tree that grows will only create apples of the type needed.

url: 500 known cultivars (varieties) of apples. Different cultivars are available for temperate and subtropical climates. One large collection of over 2
title: 100 apple cultivars is at the National Fruit Collection in England. Most of these cultivars are grown for eating fresh (dessert apples). However
text: some are grown simply for cooking or making cider. Cider apples are usually too tart to eat immediately. However
title_vector: they give cider a rich flavor that dessert apples cannot.

id: Most popular apple cultivars are soft but crisp. Colorful skin
url: easy shipping
title: disease resistance
text: 'Red Delicious' apple shape
title_vector: and popular flavor are also needed. Modern apples are usually sweeter than older cultivars. This is because popular tastes in apples have become different. Most North Americans and Europeans enjoy sweet apples. Extremely sweet apples with hardly any acid taste are popular in Asia and India.

id: In the United Kingdom there are about 3000 different types of apples. The most common apple type grown in England is the 'Bramley seedling'
url: which is a popular cooking apple.

id: Apple orchards are not as common as they were in the early 1900s
url: when apples were rarely brought in from other countries. Organizations such as Common Ground teach people about the importance of rare and local varieties of fruit.

id: Many apples are grown in temperate parts of the United States and Canada. In many areas where apple growing is important

url: https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abrahamic%20religion
title: Abrahamic religion
text: An Abrahamic Religion is a religion whose followers believe in the prophet Abraham. They believe Abraham and his sons/grandsons hold an important role in human spiritual development. The best known Abrahamic religions are Judaism, Christianity and Islam. Smaller religious traditions sometimes included as Abrahamic religions are Samaritanism, Druze, Rastafari, Babism and Bahá'í Faith. Mandaeism (a religion that holds many Abrahamic beliefs) is not called Abrahamic because its followers think Abraham was a false prophet

id: True Abrahamic religions are monotheistic (the belief that there is only one God). They also all believe that people should pray to God and worship God often. Among monotheistic religions
url: the Abrahamic religions have the world's largest number of followers. They are also all ethical monotheistic religions. This means they have rules that they have to follow.
